{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503200","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503200"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:56:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:56:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1942"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1942","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1942"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.13,0.54,0.13,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1942"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101181"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1942","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1942"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1942"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83618"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1017"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"5364"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14013"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31322"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33438"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34841"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39196"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101181"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man presents to the Gastroenterology clinic for the results of his recent colonoscopy. The colonoscopy report detailed a finding of a single polyp in the proximal colon. The colonoscopy was performed due to the patient\u0027s extensive family history of cancer. The man\u0027s father and paternal grandfather died from bowel cancer at ages 50 and 65 respectively. His paternal uncle was diagnosed with bowel cancer at age 45. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following genetic abnormalities would most likely be present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Positive RET gene mutation","Positive CDKN2A gene mutation","Positive MLH1 gene mutation","Positive BRCA2 gene mutation","Positive STK11 gene mutation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGiven his family history, the patient is in the high-risk category for colorectal cancer and should be investigated for inherited conditions. The pattern of disease in this family strongly suggests Lynch syndrome (Hereditary Non-polyposis Colorectal Cancer). This condition is inherited in an autosomal dominant pattern and is associated with mutations in DNA mismatch repair genes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPositive MLH1 gene mutation\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely finding in this case. MLH1 is one of the four main mismatch repair genes (along with MSH2, MSH6, and PMS2) associated with Lynch syndrome. Individuals with Lynch syndrome have an increased risk of developing colorectal cancer at a young age, as seen in this family.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPositive RET gene mutation\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia type 2 (MEN2), which typically presents with medullary thyroid carcinoma, phaeochromocytoma, and hyperparathyroidism, not colorectal cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPositive CDKN2A gene mutation\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with familial atypical multiple mole melanoma (FAMMM) syndrome and increased risk of pancreatic cancer, not primarily colorectal cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPositive BRCA2 gene mutation\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily associated with increased risks of breast and ovarian cancer. While there is a slightly increased risk of colorectal cancer, it would not typically present with the pattern seen in this family.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPositive STK11 gene mutation\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with Peutz-Jeghers syndrome, which is characterised by hamartomatous polyps throughout the gastrointestinal tract and mucocutaneous pigmentation, not the pattern described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBecause of the possibility of Lynch syndrome, the accuracy of the family history of cancer diagnoses and polyp pathology should be checked carefully and updated regularly. Consider tumour testing in affected relatives for Lynch syndrome-related changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESurveillance colonoscopy every 1 to 2 years is recommended for individuals carrying a germline mutation or clinically at risk of carrying a mutation but in whom definitive testing is not possible. It should commence at age 25 or 5 years younger than the youngest affected family member if \u0026lt; 30 years. Annual surveillance is preferred in known mutation carriers.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lynch syndrome is an autosomal dominant condition associated with mutations in DNA mismatch repair genes, most commonly MLH1, MSH2, MSH6, and PMS2.","Individuals with Lynch syndrome require regular colonoscopy surveillance starting at age 25 or 5 years younger than the youngest affected family member.","Tumour testing in affected relatives using immunohistochemistry and microsatellite instability analysis can help confirm Lynch syndrome."],"references":["Syngal S, Brand RE, Church JM et al. ACG Clinical Guideline: Genetic Testing and Management of Hereditary Gastrointestinal Cancer Syndromes. Am J Gastroenterol 2015;110(2): 223-263.","Clinical practice guidelines for the prevention, early detection and management of colorectal cancer. Cancer Council Australia. June 2024. Available at: https://app.magicapp.org/#/guideline/noPKwE/section/LG6VOw"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83618"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1942"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83618","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83618"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-30T22:01:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-18T21:08:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1942"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101181"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"42","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/42"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddec","name":"Genetics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investiga